<a href="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/jump?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" target="_blank"><img src="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/ad?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" border="0" alt=""></a>The WoF programme has been hard at work during the last few months as its firefighters prepared for the winter fire season which usually starts in early June.Yellow Card training camps will also be conducted in the northern province later this month.Environmental Affairs Minister Edna Molewa told Daily Sun: “These firefighters are professionally trained to suppress veld and forest fires.“They are sent throughout the country to reduce the personal and economic harm caused by unwanted wildfires.”WoF has also formed a national team which can be sent to any part of the country to assist farmers and landowners in the event of fires breaking out.The WoF team will launch the Community Fire Awareness campaign across the country this month.The campaign aims to teach communities to be safe from fires.“We also urge communities to be more vigilant during this fire season and not to start unnecessary fires,” she said.“Communities should also take extra care by removing unnecessary rubble on their properties because it can pose a serious fire risk.“They should cut down overhanging branches close to their properties and clean their gutters as the dry leaves that end up in these gutters also can pose a fire risk.”